5 SECTION 3. IC 15-15-13-9, AS AMENDED BY P.L.190-2019,
6 SECTION 10, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
7 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 9. (a) An agricultural hemp seed production
8 license issued under this chapter authorizes a grower or handler to
9 produce and handle agricultural hemp seed for sale to licensed hemp
10 growers and handlers. A seller of agricultural hemp seed shall ensure
11 that the seed complies with any standards set by the state seed
12 commissioner. The state seed commissioner shall make available to
13 growers information that identifies sellers of agricultural hemp seed.
14 (b) A person who sells agricultural hemp seed to a grower must be
15 a seed distributor who has a permit under IC 15-15-1-34.
16 (c) All growers and handlers must keep records in accordance with
17 rules adopted by the state seed commissioner. Upon at least three (3)
18 days notice, the state seed commissioner may audit the required records
19 during normal business hours. The state seed commissioner may
20 conduct an audit for the purpose of ensuring compliance with:
21 (1) this chapter;
22 (2) rules adopted by the state seed commissioner; or
23 (3) hemp license or agricultural hemp seed production license
24 requirements, terms, and conditions.
25 (d) In addition to an audit conducted in accordance with subsection
26 (c), the state seed commissioner may inspect independently, or in
27 cooperation with the state police department, a federal law enforcement
28 agency, or a local law enforcement agency, any hemp crop during the
29 crop's growth phase and take a representative composite sample for
30 field analysis. If a crop contains an average
31 delta-9-tetrahydrocannabinol total tetrahydrocannabinol (THC)
32 concentration (including THCA) exceeding three-tenths of one percent
33 (0.3%) on a dry weight basis, the state seed commissioner may detain,
34 seize, or embargo the crop.
35 (e) The state seed commissioner may revoke a license issued under
36 this chapter to a person that fails to cooperate with:
37 (1) the state seed commissioner;
38 (2) the state police;
39 (3) a federal law enforcement agency; or
40 (4) a local law enforcement agency;
41 in an inspection, or in the taking of a sample, under subsection (d).
42 (f) A failure to cooperate described in subsection (e) constitutes
